Science fiction writer George R.R. Martin recently had his third novel, Fever Dream, published in hardcover by Poseidon Press.

00:51.600 --> 00:57.900
Fever Dream is a science-fictional, historical horror novel which combines the vampire legend and Mississippi riverboats in the antebellum south.

00:58.080 --> 01:01.680
We asked Martin why he chose to write about a combination of vampires and riverboats.

01:01.680 --> 01:04.840
The vampires came first as I was putting the book together.

01:05.140 --> 01:07.360
I had read a fair amount about vampires.

01:08.160 --> 01:12.560
I had read other people's vampire novels before, Dracula, as well as the other books I had done recently.

01:13.140 --> 01:20.080
And I had wanted to do my own version of that legend for some time because I had a few ideas about it.

01:20.320 --> 01:26.760
But I didn't want it to be just another Dracula book, just another rehash of the same old legends.

01:26.760 --> 01:33.760
Because we've seen vampire books after vampire books are essentially just the same things spun over and over again.

01:33.820 --> 01:35.120
I think that's what tires them.

01:35.900 --> 01:41.780
And at the same time I was going through all these thoughts about vampires was the period that I was living in Dubuque, Iowa.

01:42.640 --> 01:44.780
I taught college there for three years.

01:44.940 --> 01:46.840
And Dubuque, of course, is an old river town.

01:47.560 --> 01:56.060
It was once a big steamboat manufacturing center and it's still very much imbued with the old history of the great era of steam on the Mississippi.

01:57.280 --> 02:06.560
So it was during that period while I was in Dubuque that I got interested in the steamboat.

02:06.880 --> 02:08.320
I read a fair amount about them.

02:08.780 --> 02:11.840
And once I did, the two things just seemed to come together in my mind.

02:13.360 --> 02:22.760
There's a certain romanticism, I think, a dark romanticism that clings to both the old steamboats and vampires.

02:22.760 --> 02:25.880
They're both very attractive in a certain sense.

02:26.240 --> 02:33.180
The elegant vampire and the stately, intricate, gorgeous steamboat.

02:33.360 --> 02:35.220
But they also have dark sides too, of course.

02:44.960 --> 02:51.560
In Fever Dream, the protagonist, Captain Abner Marsh, owner of a failing steamboat company, the Fever River Packet Line,

02:51.860 --> 02:58.120
realizes his lifelong dream of captaining a fast, luxurious steamboat when it becomes partners with the mysterious Joshua York.

02:58.560 --> 03:02.260
All Marsh has to do to maintain the partnership and keep the fancy steamboat

03:02.260 --> 03:06.060
as sail up and down the river and avoid questioning York's somewhat odd habits.

03:06.780 --> 03:11.480
But York begins bringing aboard a strange retina of acquaintances, all of whom have nocturnal habits.

03:11.920 --> 03:14.380
And of course Marsh has difficulty staying his curiosity.

03:14.560 --> 03:17.680
As Marsh learns about York and his friends, he discovers they are vampires.

03:18.300 --> 03:21.200
But Martin presents vampires in a manner never seen in fantasy.

03:21.580 --> 03:23.480
He explains them in rational terms.

03:24.020 --> 03:28.060
This meant including some of the legendary characteristics of vampires but leaving others out.

03:28.820 --> 03:31.140
I wanted to have rationalized vampires.

03:31.680 --> 03:43.240
I wanted to have vampires that I felt could actually exist, that were not based on, you know, vague supernatural legends and down over the years.

03:43.400 --> 03:47.080
So I had to look at each of the particular beliefs associated with vampires.

03:48.140 --> 03:52.960
Now see, is there any way that I could justify this in a rational manner?

03:52.960 --> 04:01.120
Now obviously something about vampires not coming out during day, which the vampires in my book Fever Dream do have that characteristic.

04:01.780 --> 04:03.660
Well, that's very easily explainable.

04:03.900 --> 04:06.940
It's just they're nocturnal creatures.

04:08.080 --> 04:15.560
Their skin is extremely sensitive to ultraviolet, so they burn very badly if they're exposed to daylight.

04:16.200 --> 04:17.540
So they avoid it.

04:18.500 --> 04:20.300
You can justify that easily.

04:20.300 --> 04:22.920
But you look at something they're not reflected in mirrors.

04:23.240 --> 04:27.400
I mean, there's no way to justify not being reflected in mirrors scientifically.

04:27.860 --> 04:34.260
You have to rewrite essentially all the laws governing light and reflection and refraction and so on.

04:34.540 --> 04:37.480
That's strictly a supernatural motif, so I had to get rid of that.

04:38.800 --> 04:42.800
Obviously considering that the book is about vampires on Mississippi River steamboats,

04:43.460 --> 04:47.220
I had to get rid of the one that said they can't cross running water as well.

04:47.220 --> 04:50.180
So I said, say I'll up and down the steamboat all through the book.

