07:28.280 --> 07:35.080
This is about vampires on Mississippi River Steamboats, but in a deeper sense, it's about moral choices.

07:35.980 --> 07:42.420
And one of the things that Joshua York, the vampire, says to Abner, Abner Marsh, the protagonist,

07:42.860 --> 07:47.880
and that Abner later says back to him is, you make your choices. We all make our choices.

07:48.700 --> 07:55.280
If you take the traditional vampire thing, the traditional vampire beliefs, the traditional vision of the vampire,

07:57.260 --> 08:05.420
you don't have choice. The vampire is an avatar of undying, ancient, and absolutely black evil.

08:08.000 --> 08:17.140
Well, okay, fine. That makes for good entertainment, but as it interacts with the real world, kind of a hollow construct.

08:17.740 --> 08:22.540
The real world is made up of graves. I mean, real people are made up of graves.

08:22.700 --> 08:26.020
We don't have absolute good, and we don't have absolute evils.

08:26.600 --> 08:32.140
The good and evil that we have resides in each of us, and it is a matter of moral choice.

08:33.100 --> 08:36.300
Damon Julian is a charismatic elder vampire who rejects the potion.

08:36.920 --> 08:41.360
He did make a choice he owns ago, but he also makes the choice in terms of the book at the banquet

08:41.360 --> 08:44.920
when he essentially rejects what Joshua has to offer.

08:48.540 --> 08:57.240
And states his opposition to Joshua with saying, you know, we are born. This is what we are born to be.

08:57.900 --> 09:03.080
Masters over humanity, people who take the lives of those inferior to us.

09:04.960 --> 09:11.280
And this is our nature. So he is making a choice there. He's rejecting Joshua's potion.

09:11.280 --> 09:21.040
He's rejecting the freedom from the Red Thirst that Joshua offers, and he's accepting what he thinks is of his superior nature.

09:22.000 --> 09:29.860
Martin told us that he found a close parallel between Julian's view of the human race and slavery as it existed in the south at the time of the book, 1857.

09:30.560 --> 09:38.980
Of course, there's also certain, you know, resonances there with the whole slavery thing, which I tried to put through all the way through the book.

09:39.300 --> 09:48.440
It takes place in the antebellum south, late antebellum south, and slavery, of course, is very hot then.

09:48.580 --> 09:57.520
And the whole master-slave thing that existed between blacks and whites in the south then has a kind of a fantasy reflection

09:57.520 --> 10:00.660
and a relationship between vampires and human beings.

10:01.920 --> 10:04.700
This parallel even strikes Abner Marsh as the story progresses.

10:05.760 --> 10:11.080
Abner Marsh is never an evil man. I think by nature he is a good man.

10:11.600 --> 10:15.520
But he is a man at the beginning of the book who is essentially just living his own life.

10:16.140 --> 10:24.660
And the great moral issues of his time like slavery are, you know, things he kind of hashes out over the dinner table,

10:24.660 --> 10:30.080
but never has any great personal involvement in it.

10:31.540 --> 10:37.080
But as a result of the whole experience with the steamer, fever dream, and the things that happen to him,

10:37.160 --> 10:42.620
I think that Abner Marsh changes and becomes, in essence, made as much more aware of and necessitates to make moral choices.

