Science Fiction author George R.R. Martin's latest novel is Fever Dream, a science fictional historical horror story about vampires and Mississippi riverboats.

12:31.460 --> 12:33.060
Here Martin explains the title of the book.

12:33.660 --> 12:38.980
The title of the book is taken from the name of the steamboat in the book, the fever dream is named the steamboat.

12:38.980 --> 12:47.840
And the reason Avner Marsh names the steamboat Fever Dream is because it is the boat he has always dreamed of having, the grand, luxurious, fast steamer.

12:48.340 --> 12:55.700
And because he is the president, his company is called Fever River Package Company, with that odd spelling he already inverted.

12:56.420 --> 13:01.380
Okay, that explains the origin of Fever Dream, but where did the oddly spelled Fever originate?

13:01.920 --> 13:04.000
It has to do with Captain Marsh's birthplace.

13:04.900 --> 13:09.140
He was born in Galena, Illinois.

13:10.700 --> 13:22.620
And the river Galena is located on a small tributary that comes off the Mississippi, which originally was named Fever River, F-E-V-R-E River, in the early 1800s.

13:23.560 --> 13:31.980
And Marsh, of course, was born during that period and grew up calling it, in point of fact that, and this is all historically true,

13:33.080 --> 13:43.040
the name of that river was changed to Galena River fairly early on because the town got respectable and they didn't want people thinking they were all sick there.

13:43.340 --> 13:45.880
So they thought it would be better to call it the Galena River.

13:46.240 --> 13:58.720
But Galena was a very important steamboat town and the fever in its early days, today it's nothing but a creek that's completely silted up and I've visited it and you couldn't get a robot to pop it, let alone a major steamer.

13:58.720 --> 14:11.340
But in the early 1800s, Galena was a major steamboat port and the fever or the Galena River as it later became was a very bustling little tributary indeed.

14:12.380 --> 14:16.340
We asked Martin if there were actual steamboats as fast and as luxurious as the fever dream.

14:16.880 --> 14:24.000
The dimensions of the fever dream and the capacity of her engines and so forth are modeled very closely on the eclipse.

14:25.240 --> 14:39.360
In terms of the book, the eclipse is the queen of the river, the fastest, largest and most luxurious boat and it's the one Abner Marsh aspires to displace as fastest steamer on the river and that's why he built the fever dream.

14:39.960 --> 14:50.780
The eclipse was a real historical boat of its era, the 1850s, and was considered the fastest boat of that era.

14:50.780 --> 15:05.900
It did indeed win a very famous steamboat race against the Shotwell and some people including Mark Twain put forward evidence that the fever dream was in fact the fastest steamer ever on the river.

15:05.900 --> 15:29.780
And there were later steamers in the 1870s and the 1880s that while they were not perhaps as fast as the fever dream in the book or the eclipse in real life were even more luxurious like the J.M. White, a very fast and incredibly luxurious steamer of the 1870s, 1880s.

15:30.460 --> 15:34.820
One of the interesting facts that strikes the readers that river boats were extremely short lived.

15:35.720 --> 15:57.120
That was one of the interesting things that turned up when I was researching it that kind of startled me too. I mean they're such formidable looking structures. You'd think they'd be around for ages but in fact they had a shorter lifespan than the modern car.

